<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-2-4-1-what-equiv" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>What is an equivalence?</title>
  
  <definition xml:id="def-equiv">
    <title>Logically Equivalent</title>
    
    <idx><h>equivalent</h><h>logically equivalent</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Two propositional forms are <term>logically equivalent</term> (or just <term>equivalent</term>) if and
        only if they have the same truth values.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p> 
    The notation we will use for two propositional forms being equivalent is: <m>P\equiv Q</m>
  </p>

<p>
  To show that two propositional forms are indeed equivalent at the beginning, we only have the tool of 
  truth tables at our disposal. What we will see in this first example is that no matter our choice of truth value
  for <m>P</m>, <m>\sim(\sim P)</m> has the same truth value, that is <me>P\equiv \sim(\sim P)</me>
</p>

  <example xml:id='ex-double-negation'>
  <idx><h>double negation</h></idx>
    <figure>
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
          <cell><m>P</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\sim P</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\sim(\sim P)</m></cell>
      
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>T</em></cell>
          <cell>F</cell>
          <cell><em>T</em></cell>
       
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>F</em></cell>
          <cell>T</cell>
          <cell><em>F</em></cell>
          
        </row>
       
      </tabular>
    
  </figure>
  </example>


<p>For another example lets see if <me>[P\implies Q]\equiv [(\sim P)\vee Q]</me></p>

 
    <example>
      
    <figure>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(P\implies Q)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\sim P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>[(\sim P)\vee Q]</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><em>T</em></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><em>T</em></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><em>F</em></cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><em>F</em></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><em>T</em></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><em>T</em></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell><em>T</em></cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell><em>T</em></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      
    </figure>
    <p> Thus we see that the truth values are the same for <m>[P\implies Q]</m> and <m>[(\sim P)\vee Q]</m>!</p>
  </example>

   

</subsection>